goal:
Through this course, students will be able to:
- acquire a basic knowledge of social business and its challenges in international contexts;
- understand the nature and causes of social problems;
- analyse the potentials and limitations of business activities to address various social issues; and
- improve oral and written communication skills through discussions and writing essays.

Through this course, students will be able to:
- acquire the basic knowledge for making social business plans;
- develop the skills needed to seek and find information and share ideas, work collaboratively, and explore unfamiliar areas;
- develop knowledge about the distinct perspectives of stakeholders; and
- improve oral and written communication skills through assigned activities.

The goals of this course are to enable students to:
(1) understand the significance of the twentieth-century expansion of modern whaling into the Antarctic Ocean within the global economy;
(2) analyze the market rivalry between animal fats and oils, including whale oil, and vegetable oils such as palm oil--a process referred to as “inter-fat competition”;
(3) examine products such as margarine and edible oils sold in supermarkets, trace their historical development, and explain how inter-fat competition has unfolded in practices.

By the end of the semester, students will:
-　obtain knowledge of how gender and sexuality are experienced and organized in contemporary Japanese society;
-　acquire an understanding of overtime changes in issues related to gender and sexuality;
-　be able to analyze their life experiences related to gender and sexuality from a sociological perspective.
